problem: If $f(c)=\frac{3}{2c-3}$, find $\frac{kn^2}{lm}$ when $f^{-1}(c)\times c \times f(c)$ equals the simplified fraction$\frac{kc+l}{mc+n}$, where $k,l,m,\text{ and }n$ are integers.
solution:
Apply the definition of $f$ to the identity $f(f^{-1}(c))=c$ to find \begin{align*}
c&=\frac{3}{2f^{-1}(c)-3}\quad\Rightarrow\\
c(2f^{-1}(c)-3)&=3\quad\Rightarrow\\
2f^{-1}(c)-3&=\frac{3}{c}\quad\Rightarrow\\
2f^{-1}(c)&=\frac{3}{c}+3\quad\Rightarrow\\
f^{-1}(c)&=\frac{3}{2c}+\frac{3}{2}\quad\Rightarrow\\
&=\frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{1}{c}+1\right).
\end{align*}Therefore, $f^{-1}(c)\times c \times f(c)$ can be found: \begin{align*}
f^{-1}(c)\times c \times f(c)&=\left(\frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{1}{c}+1\right)\right)\times c \times \frac{3}{2c-3}\quad\Rightarrow\\
&=\frac{3}{2}\times\frac{1+c}{c}\times c \times\frac{3}{2c-3}\quad\Rightarrow\\
&=\frac{3\times (1+c)\times 3}{2 \times (2c-3)}\quad\Rightarrow\\
&=\frac{9+9c}{4c-6}\quad\Rightarrow\\
&=\frac{9c+9}{4c-6}.
\end{align*}Thus, $k=9$, $l=9$, $m=4$, and $n=-6$. So, $\frac{kn^2}{lm}=\frac{9\times(-6)^2}{9\times 4}=\boxed{9}$.
model_solution:
Step 1: Find the inverse function $f^{-1}(c)$.
$f^{-1}(c)=\frac{3}{2c-3}$
Step 2:
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(c)&=\frac{3}{2c-3}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=\frac{3}{2\left(\frac{3}{2x-3}\right)-3}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=\frac{3}{\frac{6}{2x-3}-3}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=\frac{3}{\frac{6-9x+9}{2x-3}}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=\frac{3}{\frac{-9x+15}{2x-3}}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=\frac{6x-9}{-9x+15}\\
f^{-1}(f(x))&=-\frac{6x-9}{9x-15}\\
\end{align*}
Step 3:
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(c) \times c \times f(c) &= \left(-\frac{6x-9}{9x-15}\right)x\left(\frac{3}{2x-3}\right)\\
f^{-1}(c) \times c \times f(c) &= -\frac{3x(6x-9)}{9x(2x-3)}\\
f^{-1}(c) \times c \times f(c) &= -\frac{18x^2-27x}{18x^2-27x}
\end{align*}
Since the fractions are equal, we can cancel out the common factor $18x^2-27x$ from the numerator and denominator, which is not equal to zero, giving us: 
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(c) \times c \times f(c)&=-1\\
\end{align*}
Step 4:
\begin{align*}
-1&=\frac{kc+l}{mc+n}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\frac{kc+l}{mc+n}&=-1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad kc+l&=-mc-n\\
\Rightarrow\qquad kc+mc&=-l-n\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (k+m)c&=-(l+n)\\
\end{align*}
Since the fractions are equal, we can equate the coefficients of c on both sides:
k+m=0
and
-(l+n)=0
Step 5:
\begin{align*}
k+m&=0\\
\Rightarrow\qquad m&=-k\\
\text{and}\qquad -(l+n)&=0\\
\Rightarrow\qquad l+n&=0\\
\Rightarrow\qquad n&=-l\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
kc+m(-c)&=-(l+c)n\\
\Rightarrow\qquad kc-mc&=-ln-cn\\
\Rightarrow\qquad c(k-m)&=-n(l+c)\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
c(k-m)&=-n(l+c)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad c(k-m)&=-nl-n(c)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad c(k-m)&=-nl-n(c)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad c(k-m+n)&=-nl\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{c(k-m+n)}{-nl}&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{ck-cm+cn}{-nl}&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{ck+cn-cm}{-nl}&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{cn+ck-cm}{-nl}&=1\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\frac{cn+ck-cm}{-nl}&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad cn+ck-cm&=-nl\\
\Rightarrow\qquad cn+ck&=-nl+cm\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{cn+ck}{-nl+cm}&=1\\
\end{align*}
